# Why Are South East Asians and Black Ethnicities More Prone to Diabetes? A Comprehensive Analysis

## Introduction

Diabetes mellitus, particularly type 2 diabetes (T2D), is a global health challenge with significant variation in prevalence across different ethnic groups. South East Asians and Black ethnicities exhibit disproportionately higher risks of developing T2D compared to White populations, often at younger ages and lower body mass indices (BMI). Understanding the multifactorial reasons behind this increased susceptibility is critical for targeted prevention and management strategies. This report synthesizes current evidence to elucidate why South East Asians and Black ethnicities are more prone to diabetes, focusing on genetic, physiological, environmental, and socio-cultural factors.

---

## 1. Epidemiological Overview

### 1.1 Prevalence and Risk Comparisons

- **South East Asians**: South East Asians, including populations from India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, and neighboring countries, show a high prevalence of T2D, even at lower BMI levels. For example, South Asians in the US have a diabetes prevalence of approximately 23.3%, higher than East Asians (14.0%) and non-Hispanic Whites (12.1%) ([Cheng et al., 2019](https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2755670)).

- **Black Ethnicities**: Non-Hispanic Black Americans have a diabetes prevalence of about 20.4%, significantly higher than Whites (12.1%) ([Cheng et al., 2019](https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2755670)). Additionally, Black Americans experience more diabetes-related complications such as diabetic retinopathy and end-stage renal disease ([Healthline, 2021](https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes/diabetes-and-african-americans)).

| Ethnicity             | Diabetes Prevalence (%) | Notes                                      |
|-----------------------|------------------------|--------------------------------------------|
| South East Asians     | 22.4 - 23.3            | High prevalence despite lower BMI          |
| Non-Hispanic Blacks   | 20.4                   | Higher obesity rates but BMI less predictive|
| Non-Hispanic Whites   | 12.1                   | Baseline comparison group                   |

