## 2. Pathophysiological and Genetic Factors

### 2.1 South East Asians

- **Insulin Secretion Deficiency**: Emerging data suggest South Asians have a lower capacity for insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells, leading to less compensatory reserve when challenged by unhealthy lifestyles ([Narayan & Kanaya, 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00125-020-05132-5)).

- **Body Composition**: South Asians typically have lower lean muscle mass and higher fat deposition, especially ectopic fat in the liver and muscle, which impairs insulin action ([Narayan & Kanaya, 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00125-020-05132-5); [Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

- **Higher Body Fat at Lower BMI**: Asians have 3-5% higher total body fat than Europeans at the same BMI, with a propensity for abdominal (visceral) fat, increasing insulin resistance ([Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health, n.d.](https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/obesity-prevention-source/obesity-causes/ethnic-differences-in-bmi-and-disease-risk/)).

- **Early Life Programming**: Poor maternal nutrition and fetal undernutrition (e.g., exposure to famine) program metabolic pathways predisposing to diabetes later in life ([Narayan & Kanaya, 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00125-020-05132-5); [Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

### 2.2 Black Ethnicities

- **Insulin Resistance**: Black populations often exhibit higher insulin resistance, especially in adolescents, which is a key driver of T2D ([Healthline, 2021](https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes/diabetes-and-african-americans)).

- **Genetic Diversity and G6PD Deficiency**: The "thrifty gene" hypothesis is less applicable due to genetic diversity, but higher prevalence of G6PD deficiency combined with Western diets may contribute to risk ([Healthline, 2021](https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes/diabetes-and-african-americans)).

- **Body Composition Differences**: Blacks tend to have higher lean muscle mass and lower body fat at the same BMI compared to Whites, which may affect diabetes risk differently ([Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health, n.d.](https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/obesity-prevention-source/obesity-causes/ethnic-differences-in-bmi-and-disease-risk/)).

---

## 3. Environmental and Lifestyle Factors

### 3.1 Diet and Nutrition

- **South East Asians**: Diets high in refined carbohydrates (e.g., white rice), saturated and trans fats (e.g., palm oil), and increased fast food consumption contribute to diabetes risk ([Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

- **Black Ethnicities**: Higher prevalence of obesity linked to dietary patterns and socioeconomic factors, including limited access to nutritious food, contributes to diabetes risk ([Healthline, 2021](https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes/diabetes-and-african-americans)).

### 3.2 Physical Activity

- Urbanization and modernization have reduced physical activity in South East Asian populations, increasing diabetes risk ([Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

- Black Americans, especially women and adolescent girls, report lower physical activity levels, further increasing risk ([Healthline, 2021](https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes/diabetes-and-african-americans)).

### 3.3 Smoking and Other Factors

- Nearly 50% of adult men in Asian countries smoke regularly, which is associated with increased abdominal fat and a 45% higher risk of diabetes ([Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

- Air pollution, increasingly prevalent in Asian urban centers, may increase insulin resistance and diabetes risk ([Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

---

## 4. Socioeconomic and Cultural Influences

### 4.1 Access to Healthcare and Education

- Both South East Asian and Black populations often face barriers such as language, health literacy, and culturally inappropriate care, delaying diagnosis and management ([SBS Life, 2016](https://www.sbs.com.au/life/article/how-your-culture-could-influence-your-diabetes-risk/0n7v7n1p7)).

- Socioeconomic disparities contribute to higher stress levels, poor diet, and reduced healthcare access, exacerbating diabetes risk ([Healthline, 2021](https://www.healthline.com/health/diabetes/diabetes-and-african-americans)).

### 4.2 Cultural Practices

- Dietary habits rooted in culture, such as high oil use in South East Asian cooking or fast food consumption patterns, influence diabetes risk ([SBS Life, 2016](https://www.sbs.com.au/life/article/how-your-culture-could-influence-your-diabetes-risk/0n7v7n1p7)).

- Stigma around diabetes in some cultures may prevent early diagnosis and treatment ([SBS Life, 2016](https://www.sbs.com.au/life/article/how-your-culture-could-influence-your-diabetes-risk/0n7v7n1p7)).

---

## 5. Interaction of Factors: A Dual-Mechanism Hypothesis for South Asians

Narayan and Kanaya (2020) propose that South Asians' high diabetes susceptibility arises from two interacting mechanisms:

| Mechanism                          | Description                                                                                  |
|----------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Reduced Beta Cell Function        | Lower insulin secretion capacity limits compensation for insulin resistance                  |
| Impaired Insulin Action           | Low lean muscle mass and ectopic fat deposition in liver and muscle disrupt insulin signaling |

This dual pathway explains why South Asians develop diabetes at lower BMI and younger ages, emphasizing the need for tailored interventions ([Narayan & Kanaya, 2020](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00125-020-05132-5)).

---

## 6. Implications for Prevention and Management

### 6.1 Ethnic-Specific BMI and Waist Circumference Cutoffs

- Asians require lower BMI cutoffs for overweight and obesity (e.g., overweight at BMI ≥23, obesity at BMI ≥27) due to higher body fat at lower BMI ([Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health, n.d.](https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/obesity-prevention-source/obesity-causes/ethnic-differences-in-bmi-and-disease-risk/)).

- Waist circumference targets: ≤90 cm for men and ≤80 cm for women to better predict diabetes risk in Asians ([Asian Diabetes Prevention Initiative, n.d.](http://aadi.joslin.org/content/bmi-calculator)).

### 6.2 Lifestyle Interventions

- Healthy diets rich in fiber and unsaturated fats, minimizing trans fats and refined carbohydrates, significantly reduce diabetes risk in minority populations ([Shai et al., 2006](https://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/29/7/1585)).

- Physical activity tailored to cultural preferences (e.g., dance for Pacific Islanders) improves adherence and outcomes ([SBS Life, 2016](https://www.sbs.com.au/life/article/how-your-culture-could-influence-your-diabetes-risk/0n7v7n1p7)).

### 6.3 Addressing Socioeconomic and Cultural Barriers

- Culturally appropriate education and healthcare services are essential to improve diabetes awareness, prevention, and management ([SBS Life, 2016](https://www.sbs.com.au/life/article/how-your-culture-could-influence-your-diabetes-risk/0n7v7n1p7)).

---

## Conclusion

South East Asians and Black ethnicities exhibit higher susceptibility to type 2 diabetes due to a complex interplay of genetic predispositions, body composition differences, environmental exposures, lifestyle factors, and socioeconomic challenges. South East Asians tend to have lower insulin secretion capacity and higher ectopic fat deposition despite lower BMI, while Black populations often show higher insulin resistance and obesity prevalence influenced by social determinants. Tailored prevention and management strategies that consider ethnic-specific risk profiles, cultural contexts, and socioeconomic barriers are essential to effectively address this disparity.

